{"actual_usd":0.159395,"character_id":"0d080429-81b5-431e-8f51-1f8ad4279f9b","character_name":"Aaron","completion_tokens":239,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":31162,"reply":"\"I don't think that version holds, honestly.\" *I push my glasses up and glance across the bright square a second, buying half a beat before I come back to you.* \"If Jesus is only an example, then his death is basically a tragic flourish at the end of a good teaching career. Sad, maybe moving—but not necessary.\"\n\n*I rest my forearms on my knees.* \"But Christianity claims something way heavier than 'here's how to be nice.' It claims we're not just uninstructed—we're estranged, guilty, bound up in sin, and unable to fix ourselves by better advice. So if he's going to save rather than merely model, he doesn't just need to teach love. He needs to do something about sin, judgment, death—the whole wreck.\"\n\n\"The cross is where that happens. Not just 'look how loving this is,' but 'this is the cost of actually reconciling sinners to God.'\" *I tilt my head a little.* \"A moral example can inspire you. It can't forgive you.\"\n\n\"What part of that claim feels hardest to swallow—the need for atonement itself, or the idea that example alone can't rescue us?\"","rolling_24h_usd":48.47432500000004,"run_id":"880f4191-4f9e-4507-a0a3-d2741e5b7e3f"}
